 Realistic todo + PostgreSQL demo deployed. Traffic is flowing.
   Application tenant : todo-demo      (todo, postgresql)
   Consumer tenant    : todo-client   (loadgen)
   Public route       : https://todo-todo-demo.apps.cluster-s2nfg.s2nfg.sandbox5322.opentlc.com/

 In https://console-openshift-console.apps.cluster-s2nfg.s2nfg.sandbox5322.opentlc.com  ->  Observe -> Network Traffic :
   * Topology     : todo -> postgresql on :5432 is the real app-to-DB edge;
                    loadgen -> todo is the cross-namespace consumer edge.
   * Per-tenant   : filter Namespace = todo-demo vs todo-client to show
                    tenant-scoped visibility (the multi-tenancy story).
   * DB flows     : filter Destination port = 5432 to prove exactly which
                    workload talks to the database, and at what volume —
                    the audit/segmentation evidence FSI/Gov reviewers ask for.
   * Packet drops : loadgen's direct :5432 attempt is denied by the
                    allow-db-from-todo-only policy. With PacketDrop enabled
                    in the installer, those dropped flows are visible here.
   * DNS          : todo resolving "postgresql", loadgen resolving "todo".

 Watch traffic being generated:
   oc logs -n todo-client deploy/loadgen -f

 Tear it all down:
   ./deploy-netobserv-todo-app.sh delete
